Z Score QA

Notes: Instruction of Calculator : 1. copy raw ratios to column B (Raw Ratio) 2. Final wonsorized raw ratio and its z-score is returned in column L amd M. Use only these two columns as the final result, not the iteration 4 3. Cell O3 shows how many iterations the final result runs

Algorithm:
1. Set Iteration =1; 2. Compute z-scores (cross-sectional) for all the raw ratios in the base universe selected 1.1 If All |z-score|<5, use this z-score as the final result. Stop iterative process. 1.2 If Any |z-score| >=5, then flag any instance that has a z-score > |3| as outlier      3. Compute a new_mean and new_stdev of raw ratios from #1 that are not flagged as outliers (having a z-score with z-scores <= |3|)

4. For any raw ratios that,



5. Iteration = Iteration + 1;
6. Repeat steps 2 to 5. End process at 2.1 or until Iteration = 4, whichever is earliest.

(This iteration number is slightly off from the SQL s.p. iteration column. )
library(dplyr)
  1. build a z score function
zscore = function(data) {
  z = (data-mean(data))/sd(data)
  return(z)
}

# test
# a = c(1:10)
# zscore(a)
  1. build a winsorize function
b = case_when(
  zscore(a) <= -3 ~ mean(a[abs(zscore(a)) <= 3]) - 3*sd(a[abs(zscore(a)) <= 3]),
  zscore(a) >= 3 ~ mean(a[abs(zscore(a)) <= 3]) + 3*sd(a[abs(zscore(a)) <= 3]),
  TRUE ~ a
)
